{"title_page": "Elena Garro", "text_new": "[[File:Elena Garro.jpg|thumb|Elena Garro]]\n'''Elena Garro''' (December 11, 1916? \u2013 August 22, 1998) was a [[Mexico|Mexican]] screenwriter, journalist, dramaturg, short story writer, and novelist. She was commonly affiliated with the [[Magical Realism]] movement, though she rejected this affiliation. She is a recipient of the [[Sor Juana In\u00e9s de la Cruz Prize]].\n\n==Biography==\nElena Garro was born to a Spanish father and a Mexican mother in [[Puebla (city)|Puebla]], Mexico, the third of five children. She spent her childhood in [[Mexico City]] but moved to [[Iguala]], [[Guerrero]], during the [[Cristero War]]. She studied literature, choreography and theater in the [[National Autonomous University of Mexico]] in Mexico City, where she was an active member of Julio Bracho's theatre group. She married [[Octavio Paz]] in 1937 and began a career in literature and theater. Garro's fiction explored  political and social causes related to life in Mexico. Her citizenship status and focus on Indian rights aroused controversy in Mexico. After her divorce from Paz in 1959, Garro spent time in seclusion between Madrid and Paris in Europe until moving back to [[Cuernavaca]], Mexico in 1994.<ref>Cortes and Barrea-Marlys. Encyclopedia of Latin American Theatre. Library of Congress Cataloging-in-Publication Data. 2003. pp:301.Print</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''[[Los recuerdos del porvenir]]'', M\u00e9xico, Joaqu\u00edn Mortiz, 1963, translated as ''Recollections of Things to Come'' by Ruth L. C. Simms.  \n* ''[[Andamos huyendo Lola]]'', M\u00e9xico, Joaqu\u00edn Mortiz, 1980.\n* ''Testimonios sobre Mariana'', M\u00e9xico, Grijalbo, 1981. {{ISBN|968-419-182-0}}\n* ''[[Reencuentro de personajes]]'', M\u00e9xico, Grijalbo, 1982, {{ISBN|968-419-220-7}}\n* ''La casa junto al r\u00edo''. M\u00e9xico, Grijalbo, 1983, {{ISBN|968-419-217-7}}\n* ''Y Matarazo no llam\u00f3...'', M\u00e9xico, Grijalbo, 1991. {{ISBN|970-05-0040-3}}\n* ''In\u00e9s''. M\u00e9xico, Grijalbo, 1995, {{ISBN|970-05-0616-9}}\n* ''Busca mi esquela & Primer amor''. 2. ed. Monterrey, Ediciones Castillo, 1998. (Colecci\u00f3n M\u00e1s all\u00e1; 14) {{ISBN|968-7415-36-3}}, translated as ''First Love & Look for My Obituary: Two Novellas'', and winner of the [[Sor Juana In\u00e9s de la Cruz Prize]]\n* ''Un traje rojo para un duelo''. Monterrey, Ediciones Castillo, 1996, {{ISBN|968-7415-51-7}}\n* ''Un coraz\u00f3n en un bote de basura'', M\u00e9xico, Joaqu\u00edn Mortiz, 1996, {{ISBN|968-27-0672-6}}\n* ''Mi hermanita Magdalena'', Monterrey, Ediciones Castillo, 1998. {{ISBN|970-20-0062-9}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garro, Elena}}\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:1998 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican writers]]\n[[Category:Magic realism writers]]\n[[Category:Mexican people of Asturian descent]]\n[[Category:Mexican people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:Mexican women novelists]]\n[[Category:Mexican dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Mexican women short story writers]]\n[[Category:Mexican short story writers]]\n[[Category:Women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican women writers]]\n[[Category:People from Puebla (city)]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century short story writers]]\n[[Category:Mexican screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Mexican women screenwriters]]\n\n\n{{Mexico-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Elena Garro.jpg|thumb|Elena Garro]]\n'''Elena Garro''' (December 11, 1916? \u2013 August 22, 1998) was a [[Mexico|Mexican]] screenwriter, journalist, dramaturg, short story writer, and novelist. She was commonly affiliated with the [[Magical Realism]] movement, though she rejected this affiliation. She is a recipient of the [[Sor Juana In\u00e9s de la Cruz Prize]].\n\n==Biography==\nElena Garro was born to a Spanish father and a Mexican mother in [[Puebla (city)|Puebla]], Mexico, the third of five children. She spent her childhood in [[Mexico City]] but moved to [[Iguala]], [[Guerrero]], during the [[Cristero War]]. She studied literature, choreography and theater in the [[National Autonomous University of Mexico]] in Mexico City, where she was an active member of Julio Bracho's theatre group. She married [[Octavio Paz]] in 1937 and began a career in literature and theater. Garro's fiction explored  political and social causes related to life in Mexico. Her citizenship status and focus on Indian rights aroused controversy in Mexico. After her divorce from Paz in 1959, Garro spent time in seclusion between Madrid and Paris in Europe until moving back to [[Cuernavaca]], Mexico in 1994.<ref>Cortes and Barrea-Marlys. Encyclopedia of Latin American Theatre. Library of Congress Cataloging-in-Publication Data. 2003. pp:301.Print</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''[[Los recuerdos del porvenir]]'', M\u00e9xico, Joaqu\u00edn Mortiz, 1963, translated as ''Recollections of Things to Come'' by Ruth L. C. Simms.  \n* ''[[Andamos huyendo Lola]]'', M\u00e9xico, Joaqu\u00edn Mortiz, 1980.\n* ''Testimonios sobre Mariana'', M\u00e9xico, Grijalbo, 1981. {{ISBN|968-419-182-0}}\n* ''[[Reencuentro de personajes]]'', M\u00e9xico, Grijalbo, 1982, {{ISBN|968-419-220-7}}\n* ''La casa junto al r\u00edo''. M\u00e9xico, Grijalbo, 1983, {{ISBN|968-419-217-7}}\n* ''Y Matarazo no llam\u00f3...'', M\u00e9xico, Grijalbo, 1991. {{ISBN|970-05-0040-3}}\n* ''In\u00e9s''. M\u00e9xico, Grijalbo, 1995, {{ISBN|970-05-0616-9}}\n* ''Busca mi esquela & Primer amor''. 2. ed. Monterrey, Ediciones Castillo, 1998. (Colecci\u00f3n M\u00e1s all\u00e1; 14) {{ISBN|968-7415-36-3}}, translated as ''First Love & Look for My Obituary: Two Novellas'', and winner of the [[Sor Juana In\u00e9s de la Cruz Prize]]\n* ''Un traje rojo para un duelo''. Monterrey, Ediciones Castillo, 1996, {{ISBN|968-7415-51-7}}\n* ''Un coraz\u00f3n en un bote de basura'', M\u00e9xico, Joaqu\u00edn Mortiz, 1996, {{ISBN|968-27-0672-6}}\n* ''Mi hermanita Magdalena'', Monterrey, Ediciones Castillo, 1998. {{ISBN|970-20-0062-9}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garro, Elena}}\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:1998 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican writers]]\n[[Category:Magic realism writers]]\n[[Category:Mexican people of Asturian descent]]\n[[Category:Mexican people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:Mexican women novelists]]\n[[Category:Mexican dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Mexican women short story writers]]\n[[Category:Mexican short story writers]]\n[[Category:Women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century women writers]]\n[[Category:People from Puebla (city)]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century short story writers]]\n[[Category:Mexican screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Mexican women screenwriters]]\n\n\n{{Mexico-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elena_Garro"}
