tion   = \n| image_shield    = AUT Kirchberg am Wechsel COA.jpg\n| shield_size     = 80x110px\n| shield_link     = \n<!-- Maps           -->\n| pushpin_map         = Austria\n| pushpin_mapsize     = 270\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location within Austria\n| image_map           = \n| mapsize             = \n| map_alt             =\n| map_caption         = Location within [[Neunkirchen (Austrian district)|Neunkirchen]] district\n<!-- Location    -->\n| coordinates       = {{coord|47|37|N|16|0|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type  = Country\n| subdivision_name  = [[Austria]]\n| subdivision_type1 = [[States of Austria|State]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Lower Austria]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[District (Austria)|District]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Neunkirchen (Austrian district)|Neunkirchen]]\n| parts_type        = \n| parts_style       = para\n| p1                = \n<!-- Leaders -->\n| leader_title  = [[Burgomaster|Mayor]]\n| leader_name   = Willibald Fuchs\n| leader_party  = \n| leader_title1 = \n| leader_name1  = \n<!-- Statistics -->\n| area_footnotes   = {{Austria population Wikidata|area_footnotes}}\n| area_total_km2   = {{Austria population Wikidata|area_total_km2}}\n| area_metro_km2   = \n| elevation_m      = 581\n| elevation_max_m  = \n| elevation_min_m  = \n| population_as_of = {{Austria population Wikidata|population_as_of}}\n| population_footnotes = {{Austria population Wikidata|population_footnotes}}\n| population_total = {{Austria population Wikidata|population_total}}\n| population_urban =  \n| population_metro =  \n| population_note  = \n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| established_title = \n| established_date  = \n| timezone          = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| timezone_DST      = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset        = +1\n| utc_offset_DST    = +2\n| registration_plate = \n| postal_code_type   = [[List of postal codes in Austria|Postal code]]\n| postal_code        = 2880\n| area_code_type = [[Telephone numbers in Austria|Area code]]\n| area_code      = 02641\n| website   = [http://www.kirchberg-am-wechsel.at www.kirchberg-am-wechsel.at]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Kirchberg am Wechsel''' is a town in the district of [[Neunkirchen (Austrian district)|Neunkirchen]] in the [[Austria]]n state of [[Lower Austria]]. It is notable for hosting the [[International Wittgenstein Symposium]] since 1976 and is the home of the [[Austrian Ludwig Wittgenstein Society]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Austrina Ludwig Wittgenstein Society|url=http://www.alws.at|access-date=2020-02-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131114161932/http://www.alws.at/|archive-date=2013-11-14|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=University of Graz, Department of Philosophy|url=http://philosophie-gewi.uni-graz.at/en/researching/philosophical-societies/oesterreichische-ludwig-wittgenstein-gesellschaft/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303224042/http://philosophie-gewi.uni-graz.at/en/researching/philosophical-societies/oesterreichische-ludwig-wittgenstein-gesellschaft/|archivedate=2016-03-03}}</ref>\n\n==Population==\n{{Historical populations\n|align=left\n|1869|2242\n|1880|2211\n|1890|2264\n|1900|2346\n|1910|2633\n|1923|2497\n|1934|2639\n|1939|2502\n|1951|2483\n|1961|2406\n|1971|2365\n|1981|2393\n|1991|2394\n|2001|2347\n|2011|2366\n}}\n{{clear-left}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Cities and towns in Neunkirchen (Austrian district)}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Neunkirchen District, Austria]]\n\n\n{{LowerAustria-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kirchberg_am_Wechsel"}
{"title_page": "Ximena Escalante", "text_new": "{{short description|Mexican dramatist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox writer  <!--For more information, see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]].-->\n| name = Ximena Escalante\n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = Ximena Escalante.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 1964   <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place = [[Mexico City, Mexico]]\n| death_date =    <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation = [[Dramatist]]\n| language = [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| nationality = Mexican\n| ethnicity = \n| citizenship = Mexico\n| education = [[Real Escuela Superior de Arte Dram\u00e1tico]]\n| alma_mater = \n| period = \n| genre =         <!-- or: | genres =      -->\n| subject =       <!-- or: | subjects =    -->\n| movement = \n| notableworks =  <!-- or: | notablework = -->\n| spouse =        <!-- or: | spouses =     -->\n| partner =       <!-- or: | partners =    -->\n| children = \n| relatives = Alvaro Custodio\n| awards = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| years_active = \n| module = \n| website = \n| portaldisp =    <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n}}\n'''Ximena Escalante''' (born 1964) is a Mexican dramatist who is known for her works reinterpreting ancient Greek and other texts along with those examining the creative process of more modern writers. Born into a theatrical family in [[Mexico City]], she first wanted to be an actress but began writing when she was 16. All of her plays have been staged and most have been published both in Mexico and abroad. Her work has been translated into multiple languages and is regularly invited to events such as the HotInk, the Salon du Livre-Paris, the [[Miami International Book Fair]], the Festival Internacional del Libro in [[Guadalajara]] and at [[Banff Center for the Arts|The Banff Center]] and the Rockfeller Foundation.  In 2009, she was named an \u201cartistic creator\u201d with Mexico\u2019s [[Sistema Nacional de Creadores de Arte|Sistema Nacional de Creadores]].\n\n==Life==\nEscalante was born in Mexico City in 1964.<ref name=cdominguez>{{cite web |author=Christopher Dom\u00ednguez Michael |title= El teatro literario de Ximena Escalante |publisher= Letras Libres magazine |url= http://www.letraslibres.com/revista/convivio/el-teatro-literario-de-ximena-escalante |accessdate=March 16, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=rbenitez>{{cite journal |author=Roberto Ben\u00edtez |title= Ximena Escalante |journal= Universo |publisher=Universidad Veracruzana |volume=3 |number=129 |date=January 26, 2004 |url= https://www.uv.mx/universo/129/arte/arte04.htm |accessdate=March 16, 2015 }}</ref> She is the granddaughter of director and producer Alvaro Custodio, who founded the Teatro Cl\u00e1sico de M\u00e9xico in the 1960s.<ref name=centerstage>{{cite news|title=Mexico Center Stage with 14 Authors at Miami Book Fair International|url=http://www.banderasnews.com/1011/entbk-mexcenterstage.htm|accessdate= March 14, 2015|newspaper=Banderas News|date=2010}}</ref>\n\nBecause of her family\u2019s theatrical background, she wanted to become an actress when she was very young, but was told that she did not have the talent for this.<ref name=rbenitez/> However, her upbringing in the upper-class Condesa neighborhood in Condesa shaped her perspective on human relations, having contact with artists and intellectuals and spend time at the movies with the children of [[Alejandro Jodorowsky]].<ref name=ssierra>{{cite news |author=Sonia Sierra |title= Ximena Escalante, \"en el teatro siempre me siento sola\" |newspaper= El Universal |location=Mexico City |date=July 26, 2006 |url= http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/cultura/49409.html |accessdate=March 16, 2015 }}</ref> However, despite this and the fact that she has written screenplays, she goes to the movies today infrequently.<ref name=rbenitez/>\n\nAt age 16 she began to write stories and novels and created her first play at that time. She entered a class taught by Hugo Arg\u00fcelles and at the same time studied directing with Ludwick Margules. She then received a diploma from the Escuela de Escritores.<ref name=rbenitez/><ref name=lasvoces>{{cite web |title=Las Voces del Teatro presenta a Ximena Escalante |publisher= INBA Coordinaci\u00f3n Nacional de Literatura |date=2015 |url= http://www.literatura.bellasartes.gob.mx/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1613%3Alas-voces-del-teatro-presenta-a-ximena-escalante&catid=121%3Aboletines&Itemid=89 |accessdate=March 16, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=hayuna>{{cite press release |title= Hay una fascinaci\u00f3n por la dramaturgia: Ximena Escalante |publisher= CONACULTA |location=Mexico |date=November 19, 2010 |url= http://www.conaculta.gob.mx/detalle-nota/?id=9582|accessdate=March 16, 2015 }}</ref> She also took workshops with [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Alonso de Santos]], [[William Layton (actor)|William Layton]] and [[Juan Jos\u00e9 Gurrola]].<ref name=enciclopedia/>\n\nShe went to Spain to study her bachelors at the [[Real Escuela Superior de Arte Dram\u00e1tico]] (RESAD), majoring in writing and criticism, receiving scholarships from [[FONCA]], the Sistema Nacional de Creadores (J\u00f3venes Creadores) and the Spanish Ministry of Culture and Science.<ref name=rbenitez/><ref name=enciclopedia>{{cite web|publisher=Enciclopedia de la literatura en M\u00e9xico|title=Ximena Escalante|url=http://www.elem.mx/autor/datos/15199|accessdate=March 14, 2015}}</ref>  Since then she has combined literature theory can criticism with her creative work.<ref name=rbenitez/>\n\nEscalante has two children and her house in Mexico City is filled with momentos from her career and travels, such as photos of artists and posters from her plays.<ref name=ssierra/> When asked to describe herself she replied:\n<blockquote> How am I? I am obsessed with ideas, with themes, with people: once I have begun with an obsession, I go where it takes me. I am very intense, too. I have taken many risks and I don't care. A sense of humor in myself and in others is important to me. I like food greatly. I don\u2019t like people who do not appreciate eating. I am very sensual, I like pleasure and I share this with my friends and children. I am quite impatient and intolerant, and I like mariachi a lot. \nI try to lead a spiritual life. I spent many years studying Sufism. I love traveling because it allows me to see places, people, theaters, books, lovers and a wonderful world. I have a difficult personality, at the same time I need much love and sweetness. I have practiced Shaolinquan and I tend to be melancholy.\nI have in me a strong struggle between my need to be alone and to be in the world. I spent many hours in fiction since my childhood and adolescence. Since childhood I have been this way. My brothers and sisters said and still say that I was autistic. Reality is not easy and I deal with it through paper and resolving things.<ref name=\"ssierra\" /></blockquote>\n\n==Career==\nEscalante says she is a slow writer and says only in the later career has she become more productive.<ref name=rbenitez/> However, almost all of her work has been published, and all of her plays have been staged.<ref name=rbenitez/> Her works have been translated into English, French, German, Greek, [[Dutch language|Dutch]], Italian and [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] and have been staged in New York, Washington, [[Ohio]], Miami, Montreal, [[Ottawa]], [[Banff, Alberta|Banff]], Paris, [[Lyon]], [[Cannes]], Venice, Rome, Amsterdam, [[Rotterdam]], [[Antwerp]], [[Udine]], Athens, [[Buenos Aires]], [[Santiago de Chile]] and [[Madrid]].<ref name=casaoax>{{cite web|title=Ximena Escalante |publisher=Centro de las Artes de San Agustin |location=Oaxaca |url=http://www.casa.oaxaca.gob.mx/index.php/convocatorias/89-nuevas/1028-dramaturgia-entre-el-teatro-y-el-guion-cinematografico-ximena-escalante |accessdate=March 16, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402174939/http://www.casa.oaxaca.gob.mx/index.php/convocatorias/89-nuevas/1028-dramaturgia-entre-el-teatro-y-el-guion-cinematografico-ximena-escalante |archivedate=April 2, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=worldtalent>{{cite web|title=Ximena Escalante M\u00e9xico |url=http://wth.com.mx/esp/ximena_escalante.html |publisher=World Talent House |accessdate=March 14, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402154129/http://wth.com.mx/esp/ximena_escalante.html |archivedate=April 2, 2015 }}</ref> In Mexico, her work has been directed by the likes of [[Mauricio Garc\u00eda Lozano]] and Francisco Franco.<ref name=cdominguez/> Escalante worked with the Nouveau Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du 8 theater company in [[Lyon, France]] from 2011 to 2013 to produce a series of four plays.<ref name=casaoax/>\n\nThe playwright has worked on various publications researched theatrical production and theory. She wrote a theater column for the newspaper Reforma from 2000 to 2006 and has written for publications associated with RESAD and UNAM.<ref name=rbenitez/><ref name=worldtalent/>\n\nEscalante has participated in various workshops in writing and theatrical production and gives classes in dramatic literature in various institutions.<ref name=rbenitez/> She runs a theater workshop open to all ages, with one of her students, Pablo Iv\u00e1n Garc\u00eda, winning the Mexicali Fine Arts Prize in 2010, for his play Micro dermo abrasi\u00f3n.<ref name=hayuna/>\n\nIn 2009-2012 period, Escalante was named an \u201cArtistic Creator\u201d of the Sistema Nacional de Creadores.<ref name=lasvoces/><ref name=mamezcua/> She has been invited on various occasions to the [[Pen Voices Festival]] in New York. Her works have been presented at HotInk, the Salon du Livre-Paris, the Miami International Book Fair, the Festival Internacional del Libro in Guadalajara, The Banff Center and at the Rockfeller Foundation.<ref name=hayuna/><ref name=casaoax/><ref name=mamezcua>{{cite news |author= Melissa Amezcua |title=Encanta su pluma en Francia|url=http://www.reforma.com/aplicacioneslibre/articulo/default.aspx?id=337326&md5=9657c990ba54acd8c3b92b2e95e01bc4&ta=0dfdbac11765226904c16cb9ad1b2efe|accessdate=March 14, 2015|newspaper=REFORMA|publisher=Gente|date= September 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\nWhile Escalante has written movie and television scripts including screenplays with Alfonso Arau and Rafael Montero,<ref name=rbenitez/><ref name=lasvoces/> she has focused her career mostly on writing plays.<ref name=cdominguez/>\n\nMuch of Escalante\u2019s work is based on classic myths and stories from the Classical Greece, (especially those of Sophocles, Aeschylus and Euripides) either reinterpreting them or working with characters and other elements, especially those she considers to be relevant to contemporary life.<ref name=canal22>{{cite web |title= Ximena Escalante utiliza en el teatro a la mitolog\u00eda para expresar el presente  |publisher= Canal 22  |location=Mexico City |url= https://www.canal22.org.mx/p/search_doc.php?ndf=2102 |accessdate=March 16, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=lasvoces/> Female characters such as [[Phaedra (mythology)|Phaedra]], [[Electra]], [[Andromache]], [[Salome]] and [[Lilith]] are often the focus.<ref name=casaoax/>\n\nIn addition to works based on ancient literature, Escalante has also created works dealing with the creative struggles of more modern writers, such as Shakespeare, [[Tennessee Williams]], [[Colette]], [[Sor Juana In\u00e9s de la Cruz]]. She even wrote one about painter [[Frida Kahlo]].<ref name=casaoax/><ref name=lasvoces/><ref name=rbenitez/>\n\nIn general Escalante\u2019s works are tragedies which touch on love, passion and sexuality and the conflicts they generate. However, she does add touches of humor.<ref name=rbenitez/><ref name=lasvoces/> Plays of this type include ''Fedra y otras griegas'' (2002), ''Colette'' (2005), ''Las relaciones (sexuales) de Shakespeare (y Marlowe)'' (2012) and ''Tennessee en cuerpo y alma'' (2012) .<ref name=cdominguez/> She believes it is inevitable to have plays be at least somewhat autobiographical.<ref name=rreyes>{{cite news |author=Rosario Reyes |title= Ximena Escalante, la escritora de sus propias vivencias |newspaper= El Financiero |location=Mexico City |date=May 21, 2014 |url= http://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/after-office/ximena-escalante-la-escritora-de-sus-propias-vivencias.html |accessdate=March 16, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*1994. ''Vac\u00edo Azul'', published in the anthology ''[[Hacerle el teatro]]'' by Plaza y Valdez\n*1996. ''La siesta de Pirandello'', publisherd by RESAD \n*1997. ''Cary Grant'', published by RESAD\n*2002. ''Freda y otras griegas'', published in Cuba, France and Germany, staged in Mexico City, Paris, [[Lyon]], [[Athens]], Quebec, NY, Berlin.\n*2003. ''Yo tambi\u00e9n quiero un profeta ''staged in'' Mexico'' City, Lyon, Cannes and New York\n*2005. ''Colette''\n*2006. ''Unos cuantos piquetitos''\n*2006. ''La piel''\n*2007. ''Andr\u00f3maca Real'', performed by [[National Theatre Company of Mexico]] and  New York and Lyon.\n*2007. ''Touch\u00e9 o la er\u00f3tica del combate''\n*2008.''Monologs''  performed in Italy and Chile \n*2008. ''Electra despierta ''staged in Lyon, at the Festival de la Ciudad de M\u00e9xico and other venues in Mexico City\n*2010. ''Neurastenia''\n*2012. ''Las relaciones (sexuales) de Shakespeare (y Marlowe)''\n*2012. ''Tennessee en cuerpo y alma ''staged in Mexico City, Los Angeles and Buenos Aires \n*2014. ''Grito al cielo con todo mi coraz\u00f3n ''staged in Mexico City, Paris, Lyon, [[Bordeaux]], Athens, Panama and Uruguay\n\n===Screenplays===\n*''Stella'' an adaption of a play of the same name, commissioned by [[Alfonso Arau]]\n*''[[Carlota y ellos]]'', commissioned by [[Plethora Media Works]]\n\n=== Television ===\n*''[[Coraz\u00f3n Partido]]'' for [[Argos Comunicaci\u00f3n|Argos]]\n*''[[Vivir sin ti]]'' for [[Televisi\u00f3n Azteca|TvAzteca]]\n*''[[Prohibido Amar]]'' for TvAzteca\n*''[[C\u00f3digos Privados]]'' for [[Televisa]] with Antonio Serrano\n*''[[Como ama una mujer]]'' wioth Antonio Serrano, produced by [[Jennifer L\u00f3pez]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Escalante, Ximena}}\n[[Category:Mexican women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:21st-century Mexican writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Mexican screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Writers from Mexico City]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Mexican women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mexican dramatist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox writer  <!--For more information, see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]].-->\n| name = Ximena Escalante\n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = Ximena Escalante.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 1964   <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place = [[Mexico City, Mexico]]\n| death_date =    <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation = [[Dramatist]]\n| language = [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| nationality = Mexican\n| ethnicity = \n| citizenship = Mexico\n| education = [[Real Escuela Superior de Arte Dram\u00e1tico]]\n| alma_mater = \n| period = \n| genre =         <!-- or: | genres =      -->\n| subject =       <!-- or: | subjects =    -->\n| movement = \n| notableworks =  <!-- or: | notablework = -->\n| spouse =        <!-- or: | spouses =     -->\n| partner =       <!-- or: | partners =    -->\n| children = \n| relatives = Alvaro Custodio\n| awards = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| years_active = \n| module = \n| website = \n| portaldisp =    <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n}}\n'''Ximena Escalante''' (born 1964) is a Mexican dramatist who is known for her works reinterpreting ancient Greek and other texts along with those examining the creative process of more modern writers. Born into a theatrical family in [[Mexico City]], she first wanted to be an actress but began writing when she was 16. All of her plays have been staged and most have been published both in Mexico and abroad. Her work has been translated into multiple languages and is regularly invited to events such as the HotInk, the Salon du Livre-Paris, the [[Miami International Book Fair]], the Festival Internacional del Libro in [[Guadalajara]] and at [[Banff Center for the Arts|The Banff Center]] and the Rockfeller Foundation.  In 2009, she was named an \u201cartistic creator\u201d with Mexico\u2019s [[Sistema Nacional de Creadores de Arte|Sistema Nacional de Creadores]].\n\n==Life==\nEscalante was born in Mexico City in 1964.<ref name=cdominguez>{{cite web |author=Christopher Dom\u00ednguez Michael |title= El teatro literario de Ximena Escalante |publisher= Letras Libres magazine |url= http://www.letraslibres.com/revista/convivio/el-teatro-literario-de-ximena-escalante |accessdate=March 16, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=rbenitez>{{cite journal |author=Roberto Ben\u00edtez |title= Ximena Escalante |journal= Universo |publisher=Universidad Veracruzana |volume=3 |number=129 |date=January 26, 2004 |url= https://www.uv.mx/universo/129/arte/arte04.htm |accessdate=March 16, 2015 }}</ref> She is the granddaughter of director and producer Alvaro Custodio, who founded the Teatro Cl\u00e1sico de M\u00e9xico in the 1960s.<ref name=centerstage>{{cite news|title=Mexico Center Stage with 14 Authors at Miami Book Fair International|url=http://www.banderasnews.com/1011/entbk-mexcenterstage.htm|accessdate= March 14, 2015|newspaper=Banderas News|date=2010}}</ref>\n\nBecause of her family\u2019s theatrical background, she wanted to become an actress when she was very young, but was told that she did not have the talent for this.<ref name=rbenitez/> However, her upbringing in the upper-class Condesa neighborhood in Condesa shaped her perspective on human relations, having contact with artists and intellectuals and spend time at the movies with the children of [[Alejandro Jodorowsky]].<ref name=ssierra>{{cite news |author=Sonia Sierra |title= Ximena Escalante, \"en el teatro siempre me siento sola\" |newspaper= El Universal |location=Mexico City |date=July 26, 2006 |url= http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/cultura/49409.html |accessdate=March 16, 2015 }}</ref> However, despite this and the fact that she has written screenplays, she goes to the movies today infrequently.<ref name=rbenitez/>\n\nAt age 16 she began to write stories and novels and created her first play at that time. She entered a class taught by Hugo Arg\u00fcelles and at the same time studied directing with Ludwick Margules. She then received a diploma from the Escuela de Escritores.<ref name=rbenitez/><ref name=lasvoces>{{cite web |title=Las Voces del Teatro presenta a Ximena Escalante |publisher= INBA Coordinaci\u00f3n Nacional de Literatura |date=2015 |url= http://www.literatura.bellasartes.gob.mx/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1613%3Alas-voces-del-teatro-presenta-a-ximena-escalante&catid=121%3Aboletines&Itemid=89 |accessdate=March 16, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=hayuna>{{cite press release |title= Hay una fascinaci\u00f3n por la dramaturgia: Ximena Escalante |publisher= CONACULTA |location=Mexico |date=November 19, 2010 |url= http://www.conaculta.gob.mx/detalle-nota/?id=9582|accessdate=March 16, 2015 }}</ref> She also took workshops with [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Alonso de Santos]], [[William Layton (actor)|William Layton]] and [[Juan Jos\u00e9 Gurrola]].<ref name=enciclopedia/>\n\nShe went to Spain to study her bachelors at the [[Real Escuela Superior de Arte Dram\u00e1tico]] (RESAD), majoring in writing and criticism, receiving scholarships from [[FONCA]], the Sistema Nacional de Creadores (J\u00f3venes Creadores) and the Spanish Ministry of Culture and Science.<ref name=rbenitez/><ref name=enciclopedia>{{cite web|publisher=Enciclopedia de la literatura en M\u00e9xico|title=Ximena Escalante|url=http://www.elem.mx/autor/datos/15199|accessdate=March 14, 2015}}</ref>  Since then she has combined literature theory can criticism with her creative work.<ref name=rbenitez/>\n\nEscalante has two children and her house in Mexico City is filled with momentos from her career and travels, such as photos of artists and posters from her plays.<ref name=ssierra/> When asked to describe herself she replied:\n<blockquote> How am I? I am obsessed with ideas, with themes, with people: once I have begun with an obsession, I go where it takes me. I am very intense, too. I have taken many risks and I don't care. A sense of humor in myself and in others is important to me. I like food greatly. I don\u2019t like people who do not appreciate eating. I am very sensual, I like pleasure and I share this with my friends and children. I am quite impatient and intolerant, and I like mariachi a lot. \nI try to lead a spiritual life. I spent many years studying Sufism. I love traveling because it allows me to see places, people, theaters, books, lovers and a wonderful world. I have a difficult personality, at the same time I need much love and sweetness. I have practiced Shaolinquan and I tend to be melancholy.\nI have in me a strong struggle between my need to be alone and to be in the world. I spent many hours in fiction since my childhood and adolescence. Since childhood I have been this way. My brothers and sisters said and still say that I was autistic. Reality is not easy and I deal with it through paper and resolving things.<ref name=\"ssierra\" /></blockquote>\n\n==Career==\nEscalante says she is a slow writer and says only in the later career has she become more productive.<ref name=rbenitez/> However, almost all of her work has been published, and all of her plays have been staged.<ref name=rbenitez/> Her works have been translated into English, French, German, Greek, [[Dutch language|Dutch]], Italian and [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] and have been staged in New York, Washington, [[Ohio]], Miami, Montreal, [[Ottawa]], [[Banff, Alberta|Banff]], Paris, [[Lyon]], [[Cannes]], Venice, Rome, Amsterdam, [[Rotterdam]], [[Antwerp]], [[Udine]], Athens, [[Buenos Aires]], [[Santiago de Chile]] and [[Madrid]].<ref name=casaoax>{{cite web|title=Ximena Escalante |publisher=Centro de las Artes de San Agustin |location=Oaxaca |url=http://www.casa.oaxaca.gob.mx/index.php/convocatorias/89-nuevas/1028-dramaturgia-entre-el-teatro-y-el-guion-cinematografico-ximena-escalante |accessdate=March 16, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402174939/http://www.casa.oaxaca.gob.mx/index.php/convocatorias/89-nuevas/1028-dramaturgia-entre-el-teatro-y-el-guion-cinematografico-ximena-escalante |archivedate=April 2, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=worldtalent>{{cite web|title=Ximena Escalante M\u00e9xico |url=http://wth.com.mx/esp/ximena_escalante.html |publisher=World Talent House |accessdate=March 14, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402154129/http://wth.com.mx/esp/ximena_escalante.html |archivedate=April 2, 2015 }}</ref> In Mexico, her work has been directed by the likes of [[Mauricio Garc\u00eda Lozano]] and Francisco Franco.<ref name=cdominguez/> Escalante worked with the Nouveau Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du 8 theater company in [[Lyon, France]] from 2011 to 2013 to produce a series of four plays.<ref name=casaoax/>\n\nThe playwright has worked on various publications researched theatrical production and theory. She wrote a theater column for the newspaper Reforma from 2000 to 2006 and has written for publications associated with RESAD and UNAM.<ref name=rbenitez/><ref name=worldtalent/>\n\nEscalante has participated in various workshops in writing and theatrical production and gives classes in dramatic literature in various institutions.<ref name=rbenitez/> She runs a theater workshop open to all ages, with one of her students, Pablo Iv\u00e1n Garc\u00eda, winning the Mexicali Fine Arts Prize in 2010, for his play Micro dermo abrasi\u00f3n.<ref name=hayuna/>\n\nIn 2009-2012 period, Escalante was named an \u201cArtistic Creator\u201d of the Sistema Nacional de Creadores.<ref name=lasvoces/><ref name=mamezcua/> She has been invited on various occasions to the [[Pen Voices Festival]] in New York. Her works have been presented at HotInk, the Salon du Livre-Paris, the Miami International Book Fair, the Festival Internacional del Libro in Guadalajara, The Banff Center and at the Rockfeller Foundation.<ref name=hayuna/><ref name=casaoax/><ref name=mamezcua>{{cite news |author= Melissa Amezcua |title=Encanta su pluma en Francia|url=http://www.reforma.com/aplicacioneslibre/articulo/default.aspx?id=337326&md5=9657c990ba54acd8c3b92b2e95e01bc4&ta=0dfdbac11765226904c16cb9ad1b2efe|accessdate=March 14, 2015|newspaper=REFORMA|publisher=Gente|date= September 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\nWhile Escalante has written movie and television scripts including screenplays with Alfonso Arau and Rafael Montero,<ref name=rbenitez/><ref name=lasvoces/> she has focused her career mostly on writing plays.<ref name=cdominguez/>\n\nMuch of Escalante\u2019s work is based on classic myths and stories from the Classical Greece, (especially those of Sophocles, Aeschylus and Euripides) either reinterpreting them or working with characters and other elements, especially those she considers to be relevant to contemporary life.<ref name=canal22>{{cite web |title= Ximena Escalante utiliza en el teatro a la mitolog\u00eda para expresar el presente  |publisher= Canal 22  |location=Mexico City |url= https://www.canal22.org.mx/p/search_doc.php?ndf=2102 |accessdate=March 16, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=lasvoces/> Female characters such as [[Phaedra (mythology)|Phaedra]], [[Electra]], [[Andromache]], [[Salome]] and [[Lilith]] are often the focus.<ref name=casaoax/>\n\nIn addition to works based on ancient literature, Escalante has also created works dealing with the creative struggles of more modern writers, such as Shakespeare, [[Tennessee Williams]], [[Colette]], [[Sor Juana In\u00e9s de la Cruz]]. She even wrote one about painter [[Frida Kahlo]].<ref name=casaoax/><ref name=lasvoces/><ref name=rbenitez/>\n\nIn general Escalante\u2019s works are tragedies which touch on love, passion and sexuality and the conflicts they generate. However, she does add touches of humor.<ref name=rbenitez/><ref name=lasvoces/> Plays of this type include ''Fedra y otras griegas'' (2002), ''Colette'' (2005), ''Las relaciones (sexuales) de Shakespeare (y Marlowe)'' (2012) and ''Tennessee en cuerpo y alma'' (2012) .<ref name=cdominguez/> She believes it is inevitable to have plays be at least somewhat autobiographical.<ref name=rreyes>{{cite news |author=Rosario Reyes |title= Ximena Escalante, la escritora de sus propias vivencias |newspaper= El Financiero |location=Mexico City |date=May 21, 2014 |url= http://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/after-office/ximena-escalante-la-escritora-de-sus-propias-vivencias.html |accessdate=March 16, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*1994. ''Vac\u00edo Azul'', published in the anthology ''[[Hacerle el teatro]]'' by Plaza y Valdez\n*1996. ''La siesta de Pirandello'', publisherd by RESAD \n*1997. ''Cary Grant'', published by RESAD\n*2002. ''Freda y otras griegas'', published in Cuba, France and Germany, staged in Mexico City, Paris, [[Lyon]], [[Athens]], Quebec, NY, Berlin.\n*2003. ''Yo tambi\u00e9n quiero un profeta ''staged in'' Mexico'' City, Lyon, Cannes and New York\n*2005. ''Colette''\n*2006. ''Unos cuantos piquetitos''\n*2006. ''La piel''\n*2007. ''Andr\u00f3maca Real'', performed by [[National Theatre Company of Mexico]] and  New York and Lyon.\n*2007. ''Touch\u00e9 o la er\u00f3tica del combate''\n*2008.''Monologs''  performed in Italy and Chile \n*2008. ''Electra despierta ''staged in Lyon, at the Festival de la Ciudad de M\u00e9xico and other venues in Mexico City\n*2010. ''Neurastenia''\n*2012. ''Las relaciones (sexuales) de Shakespeare (y Marlowe)''\n*2012. ''Tennessee en cuerpo y alma ''staged in Mexico City, Los Angeles and Buenos Aires \n*2014. ''Grito al cielo con todo mi coraz\u00f3n ''staged in Mexico City, Paris, Lyon, [[Bordeaux]], Athens, Panama and Uruguay\n\n===Screenplays===\n*''Stella'' an adaption of a play of the same name, commissioned by [[Alfonso Arau]]\n*''[[Carlota y ellos]]'', commissioned by [[Plethora Media Works]]\n\n=== Television ===\n*''[[Coraz\u00f3n Partido]]'' for [[Argos Comunicaci\u00f3n|Argos]]\n*''[[Vivir sin ti]]'' for [[Televisi\u00f3n Azteca|TvAzteca]]\n*''[[Prohibido Amar]]'' for TvAzteca\n*''[[C\u00f3digos Privados]]'' for [[Televisa]] with Antonio Serrano\n*''[[Como ama una mujer]]'' wioth Antonio Serrano, produced by [[Jennifer L\u00f3pez]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Escalante, Ximena}}\n[[Category:Mexican women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:21st-century Mexican writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Mexican screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Writers from Mexico City]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Mexican women writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ximena_Escalante"}
